== The Bradley Method Daily Routine

The Bradley Method, developed by Dr. Robert Bradley in 1947, is one of the few childbirth education approaches that prescribes a specific, daily exercise regimen as a core part of labor preparation --- not as a suggestion, but as an integral component of the method.#citation[2] Bradley's premise was straightforward: if labor is physical work, women should train for it the way an athlete trains for a competition. His daily routine focuses on four exercises that target the specific muscle groups and movement patterns used during labor.

The Bradley Method emphasizes that these exercises should be practiced _every day_ throughout pregnancy, not just in the third trimester. The cumulative effect of months of daily practice is substantially different from a few weeks of sporadic effort. That said, starting at any point in pregnancy is better than not starting at all.

=== Tailor Sitting (Butterfly Stretch)

*What it is:* Sit on the floor with the soles of your feet together and your knees dropped out to the sides, like a butterfly's wings. Gently press your knees toward the floor using your elbows or hands. Hold the position while keeping your back straight.

*Why it matters for labor:* Tailor sitting stretches the inner thighs, opens the pelvis, and improves flexibility in the hip joints --- all of which matter during pushing, particularly if you deliver in a squatting, semi-reclined, or hands-and-knees position. The stretch also encourages blood flow to the pelvic area.

*How to practice:*
- Sit in this position whenever you're on the floor --- watching television, reading, folding laundry
- Hold for 5 to 10 minutes at a time, or longer as comfort allows
- Gently press your knees down with your elbows, hold for 10 to 15 seconds, release, repeat
- You should feel a stretch, not pain --- never force your knees down
- The Bradley Method recommends this as your default sitting position on the floor throughout pregnancy#citation[2]

=== Pelvic Rocking (Cat-Cow on Hands and Knees)

*What it is:* Get on your hands and knees with your hands directly under your shoulders and your knees under your hips. Slowly arch your back upward (like an angry cat), tucking your pelvis under. Then slowly release, letting your belly drop and your back return to a neutral position (or a gentle sway). Move between these positions in a slow, rhythmic motion.

*Why it matters for labor:* Pelvic rocking strengthens the lower back, relieves back pain (one of the most common pregnancy complaints), and improves the flexibility and mobility of the pelvis. During labor, the hands-and-knees position is one of the most effective for managing back labor and encouraging a posterior baby to rotate into a more favorable position. Women who have practiced pelvic rocking throughout pregnancy are already comfortable and strong in this position when they need it most.

*How to practice:*
- Perform 40 to 80 pelvic rocks twice daily (morning and evening)
- Move slowly --- this is not a speed exercise
- Breathe naturally, inhaling as your back goes flat and exhaling as you arch upward
- Focus on the movement originating from your pelvis, not your shoulders
- This exercise is particularly effective for relieving lower back pain and can be done any time your back is bothering you
- The Bradley Method recommends this as one of the most important exercises in the entire routine#citation[2]

=== Squatting Practice

*What it is:* Stand with your feet slightly wider than hip-width apart, toes turned slightly outward. Lower yourself into a deep squat, keeping your heels on the floor if possible. Hold the squat, then rise back up. If balance is an issue, hold onto a sturdy chair, countertop, or your partner's hands.

*Why it matters for labor:* Squatting opens the pelvic outlet by up to 28 to 30 percent compared to lying on your back.#citation[4] This is not a small difference --- it is the difference between your baby having significantly more room to descend and rotate through the birth canal. Squatting also uses gravity to assist the baby's descent and engages the muscles of the pelvic floor in a way that supports effective pushing. Many traditional birthing cultures around the world use squatting as the primary delivery position, and for good reason.

*How to practice:*
- Start with supported squats (holding a chair or counter) if you cannot yet squat comfortably
- Hold the squat for 15 to 30 seconds, gradually increasing to 60 seconds or longer
- Practice 5 to 10 squats daily
- Keep your heels on the floor --- if they lift, try widening your stance or placing a rolled towel under your heels
- Focus on keeping your chest up and your back straight, not rounded forward
- As you gain strength and flexibility, practice squatting during daily activities: picking things up from the floor, organizing low shelves, playing with other children

=== Kegel Exercises

*What they are:* Kegels are contractions of the pelvic floor muscles --- the muscles you use to stop the flow of urine midstream. A Kegel involves squeezing these muscles, holding the contraction, and then fully releasing.

*Why they matter for labor:* The pelvic floor muscles are the muscles that support your baby's weight throughout pregnancy, that you engage during pushing, and that need to recover after delivery. Strong pelvic floor muscles give you more control during the pushing stage and are associated with more effective pushing efforts. Equally important, a pelvic floor that can fully _relax_ allows the baby to pass through the birth canal more easily. Kegels train both the contraction and the release.#citation[3]

*How to practice:*
- Contract your pelvic floor muscles as if you are stopping the flow of urine
- Hold for 5 seconds, then fully relax for 5 seconds
- Work up to holding for 10 seconds with 10 seconds of relaxation
- Perform 3 sets of 10 repetitions daily
- Equally important: practice the _release_ portion. During labor, you need to be able to fully relax these muscles on command. Many women focus only on the squeeze and neglect the release --- train both
- You can do Kegels anywhere --- sitting at your desk, waiting in line, driving, lying in bed
- The Bradley Method recommends Kegels as a daily, non-negotiable part of the routine#citation[2]

*A common mistake:* Many women bear down or tighten their abdominal muscles, buttocks, or thighs instead of isolating the pelvic floor. If your stomach or glutes are visibly tensing, you are using the wrong muscles. The contraction should be internal --- an upward lifting sensation, as if you are drawing the pelvic floor up toward your belly button.

