== Pelvic Floor Exercises in Detail

The four Bradley Method exercises above provide the foundation, but several additional exercises and practices deserve their own detailed coverage because of their direct impact on labor and recovery.

=== Kegels: Getting Them Right

Many women have been told to "do their Kegels" but have never been taught how to do them correctly. Research suggests that up to 30 percent of women perform Kegels incorrectly when given only verbal instructions.#citation[3] Here is a more detailed guide.

*Finding the right muscles:*
- The next time you urinate, try to stop the flow midstream. The muscles you use to do this are your pelvic floor muscles. (Use this technique only for identification purposes --- do not regularly practice Kegels while urinating, as this can interfere with complete bladder emptying.)
- Another way to identify them: insert a clean finger into your vagina and squeeze as if you are holding in urine. You should feel pressure around your finger.
- A third option: imagine you are trying to pick up a marble with your vagina. The lifting, drawing-in sensation is the correct contraction.

*A complete Kegel routine:*
- *Quick flicks:* Contract and release rapidly --- squeeze for 1 second, release for 1 second. Do 10 in a row. These train fast-twitch muscle fibers.
- *Sustained holds:* Contract and hold for 5 to 10 seconds, then fully relax for 5 to 10 seconds. Do 10 in a row. These train slow-twitch endurance fibers.
- *The elevator:* Imagine your pelvic floor is an elevator. Squeeze gradually to the "first floor" (light contraction), then the "second floor" (moderate), then the "third floor" (maximum contraction). Hold at the top for 5 seconds, then slowly lower back down through each floor. This trains fine motor control, which matters during pushing.
- *Practice fully releasing.* After each set, consciously release your pelvic floor completely. Let everything go. This release is what you need during the pushing stage of labor. A pelvic floor that can only clench but cannot fully relax will work against you during delivery.

*Frequency:* Aim for 3 sets of 10 repetitions (mixing quick flicks and sustained holds) at least 3 times per day. Many practitioners recommend working up to 100 total Kegels per day throughout pregnancy.

=== Squats: Variations and Benefits

Beyond the basic squat described in the Bradley routine, several variations offer specific benefits.

*Supported deep squat (malasana):* With feet wider than hip-width, lower into a deep squat and bring your hands together at your chest in a prayer position. Use your elbows to gently press your knees outward. Hold for 30 to 60 seconds. This is a yoga-based variation that maximizes pelvic opening.

*Wall squat:* Place your back against a wall and slide down into a squat position, keeping your thighs parallel to the floor. Hold for 15 to 30 seconds. This is easier on the knees and good for building leg endurance.

*Partner-supported squat:* Face your partner and hold each other's forearms. Both of you squat down together, using each other for counterbalance. This is the most practical variation because it mimics the supported squatting position many women use during labor.

*Squat holds during daily life:* Instead of bending at the waist to pick something up, squat down. Instead of sitting in a chair to fold laundry, squat on the floor. The more squatting becomes part of your daily movement pattern, the more natural and sustainable the position will be during labor.

*The 30% advantage:* Research has consistently shown that squatting increases the pelvic outlet diameter by approximately 28 to 30 percent compared to the lithotomy position (lying on your back with legs in stirrups).#citation[4] This is a significant mechanical advantage during the pushing stage. The combination of a wider pelvic outlet and the assistance of gravity makes squatting one of the most physiologically effective pushing positions available.

=== Pelvic Tilts

*What they are:* Lie on your back with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor (in early pregnancy) or perform standing against a wall (as pregnancy progresses and lying flat becomes uncomfortable). Press the small of your back flat against the floor or wall by gently tilting your pelvis upward. Hold for 5 seconds, then release.

*Why they matter:*
- *Back pain relief:* Pelvic tilts are one of the most effective exercises for pregnancy-related lower back pain. As your belly grows and your center of gravity shifts forward, the curve in your lower back increases, creating strain. Pelvic tilts counteract this by strengthening the abdominal and lower back muscles that support your spine.
- *Baby positioning:* Pelvic tilts, particularly when combined with hands-and-knees positioning, can help encourage a posterior-facing baby (sunny-side up) to rotate into the anterior position (facing your back), which is the most favorable position for labor.#citation[5]
- *Core engagement:* The gentle abdominal contraction involved in a pelvic tilt strengthens the deep transverse abdominis --- the core muscle that wraps around your midsection like a corset. This muscle supports your uterus during pregnancy and is essential for postpartum recovery.

*How to practice:*
- Standing: Stand with your back against a wall, feet about 12 inches from the wall. Press the small of your back flat against the wall by tilting your pelvis. Hold 5 seconds, release. Repeat 10 to 20 times.
- On hands and knees: This is essentially the pelvic rocking exercise described above. The hands-and-knees variation adds the benefit of gravity working with you to encourage baby positioning.
- Lying down (first trimester or short durations): Lie on your back with knees bent, press the small of your back into the floor. After the first trimester, keep the duration brief or use a wedge pillow to avoid compression of the vena cava.
- Perform 20 to 40 pelvic tilts twice daily.

=== Perineal Massage

*What it is:* Perineal massage is a technique that involves gently stretching the tissues of the perineum --- the area between the vagina and the anus --- in preparation for the stretching that occurs during delivery. It is typically begun around 34 to 36 weeks of pregnancy.

*Why it matters:* A 2013 Cochrane review found that women who practiced perineal massage in the final weeks of pregnancy had a statistically significant reduction in perineal trauma requiring stitching and a reduction in the rate of episiotomy, particularly among first-time mothers.#citation[6] The massage works by increasing the elasticity of the perineal tissues and helping women become familiar with the stretching and pressure sensations they will experience during crowning.

*How to practice:*
- Wash your hands thoroughly. Use a natural lubricant (coconut oil, olive oil, or a water-based lubricant).
- Insert your thumbs (or your partner's thumbs) about 1 to 1.5 inches into the vagina.
- Press downward toward the rectum and to the sides, stretching the tissue until you feel a tingling or burning sensation --- this is similar to the "ring of fire" sensation you will feel during crowning.
- Hold the stretch for 1 to 2 minutes, breathing deeply and consciously relaxing into the sensation rather than tensing against it.
- Gently massage the lower half of the vaginal opening in a U-shaped motion.
- Practice for 5 to 10 minutes, 3 to 4 times per week, starting around 34 to 36 weeks.
- Your partner can do this for you, which has the added benefit of involving them in the physical preparation and helping them understand what the perineal area goes through during birth.

*The relaxation connection:* Perineal massage is also a relaxation training exercise in disguise. The sensation is uncomfortable --- intentionally so. Learning to breathe through the discomfort and relax your pelvic floor while experiencing a stretching, burning sensation is exactly what you will need to do when your baby is crowning. Women who have practiced perineal massage often describe the crowning sensation as familiar rather than shocking.

