== How Exercises Help During Labor

The exercises described in this chapter are not theoretical. Each one connects directly to specific demands of labor.

*Stronger pelvic floor = more effective pushing.* The pelvic floor muscles are the muscles you engage during the pushing stage. Women with stronger pelvic floors can push more effectively and with better control, which can shorten the second stage of labor. Equally important, a pelvic floor that has been trained to fully relax can open and stretch to allow the baby through, reducing the need for episiotomy or assisted delivery.#citation[3]

*Squatting opens the pelvis by up to 30%.* This is one of the most dramatic mechanical advantages available during pushing. A woman who has been practicing squats for months can maintain a deep squat during contractions without her legs giving out, allowing her to push in the position that gives her baby the most room.#citation[4]

*Relaxation training reduces the perception of pain.* Women who have practiced progressive muscle relaxation and breathing techniques throughout pregnancy consistently report lower pain scores during labor compared to women who have not.#citation[1] This is not a placebo effect --- relaxed muscles create less resistance to the uterus's work, produce fewer stress hormones, and allow the body's natural endorphin system to function more effectively.

*Partner knowing support positions = better labor support.* Research consistently shows that continuous, knowledgeable support during labor is associated with shorter labors, fewer interventions, less pain medication, fewer cesarean births, and higher maternal satisfaction.#citation[8] A partner who has practiced counter-pressure, hip squeezes, massage techniques, and supported positions is a partner who can provide this support confidently, without hesitation or uncertainty.

*General fitness = more stamina for labor.* Labor is a marathon, not a sprint. First-time mothers average 12 to 24 hours of labor, and pushing alone can last over an hour. Cardiovascular fitness, muscular endurance, and the ability to sustain effort over many hours all contribute to a mother's ability to remain active and engaged throughout labor rather than depleted and exhausted.

