== How Exercises Help Post-Labor Recovery

The benefits of prenatal exercise do not end when the baby is born. The strength and fitness you build during pregnancy pay direct dividends in the postpartum period.

*Stronger pelvic floor recovers faster.* The pelvic floor undergoes enormous stress during vaginal delivery. Women who enter labor with a strong, well-conditioned pelvic floor recover muscle tone and function faster than those who do not. This translates to less urinary incontinence (a common postpartum complaint), faster return of pelvic organ support, and earlier return to comfortable physical activity.#citation[3]

*Core strength aids in postpartum healing.* The transverse abdominis and other deep core muscles that you strengthen through pelvic tilts and exercises during pregnancy are the same muscles responsible for supporting your spine, pelvis, and organs during the postpartum period. Stronger core muscles reduce the severity of diastasis recti (the separation of the abdominal muscles that commonly occurs during pregnancy) and support faster functional recovery.

*Exercise habits established during pregnancy carry into postpartum.* Women who exercise consistently during pregnancy are significantly more likely to resume exercise in the postpartum period than women who are sedentary during pregnancy.#citation[9] This matters because postpartum exercise is associated with reduced rates of postpartum depression, faster physical recovery, improved sleep quality, and better overall well-being. The daily habit you build now --- even if it is just 15 to 20 minutes of floor exercises --- creates a foundation that carries forward into one of the most physically and emotionally demanding periods of your life.

*Perineal preparation reduces recovery time.* Women who practiced perineal massage in the third trimester and experienced less tearing during delivery have shorter perineal healing times, less pain during the postpartum period, and earlier return to comfortable sitting and walking.#citation[6]

