#our-take[
  == Our Take

  We lean toward daily practice making a real, measurable difference in labor outcomes and postpartum recovery. This is not one of those areas where the evidence is ambiguous or the benefits are marginal. Women who prepare their bodies for labor through targeted exercise consistently have better outcomes across nearly every metric that matters --- shorter labors, more effective pushing, less perceived pain, fewer interventions, and faster recovery.

  The Bradley Method deserves specific mention here as one of the most comprehensive exercise-based approaches to labor preparation. Its daily routine of tailor sitting, pelvic rocking, squatting, and Kegels --- combined with its emphasis on relaxation training and partner involvement --- is a complete preparation system, not just a list of stretches. If you are looking for a structured approach, the Bradley Method's exercise protocol is an excellent starting point.

  That said, we know that not every woman is going to do a full 20-minute routine every single day of her pregnancy. Life happens. Energy fluctuates. Some days you are exhausted and the last thing you want to do is squat. That is completely fine. Even doing _some_ of these exercises _some_ of the time is better than doing none of them. If all you manage is Kegels while brushing your teeth and a few squats while picking things up off the floor, you are still further ahead than if you did nothing.

  The partner exercises deserve special emphasis. The single most common regret we hear from partners after birth is "I didn't know what to do." Counter-pressure, hip squeezes, and massage are simple techniques, but they need to be practiced. A partner who has rehearsed these techniques can provide immediate, confident support during labor. A partner who is encountering them for the first time in the delivery room will be fumbling when their partner needs them most.

  Always consult with your provider about what exercises are safe for your specific situation. Most of the exercises described in this chapter are safe for uncomplicated pregnancies, but if you have a high-risk condition, placenta previa, preterm labor concerns, or other medical considerations, your provider may modify or restrict certain activities.
